  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Landlord insurance is something most Brisbane investors take out shortly after settling a rental property and rarely think about again until they make a claim or sell. The selling phase is exactly where landlord insurance becomes most important and most commonly mishandled. Sellers cancel cover too early to save a few hundred dollars in premium. Tenants vacate ahead of settlement and the property sits uninsured because nobody told the insurer. A storm or fire occurs in the gap between contract and settlement and the seller, no longer the formal owner of record in their own mind, discovers they are still legally responsible for the loss.</p>

      <p>The principle in Queensland is clear: until settlement, the risk of loss to the property stays with the seller. Damage, theft, malicious destruction, fire, storm, or flood between contract date and settlement is the seller's problem to fix. The contract obliges the seller to deliver the property in the condition agreed at exchange, and if that has changed, the seller carries the cost of putting it right. Without insurance, that cost lands directly on the seller's bank balance. With insurance, most of it lands on the insurer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What landlord insurance covers</h2>
      <p>A typical Queensland landlord insurance policy bundles several protections into one product. The components most commonly included are: building cover for the structure of the property itself (foundations, walls, roof, fixtures), rent default protection if the tenant stops paying or breaks the lease, malicious damage cover for tenant-caused damage beyond what the bond covers, public liability cover for injuries to third parties on the property, contents cover for any landlord-owned items inside the property (carpets, blinds, appliances), and loss of rent cover for periods the property is uninhabitable due to an insured event.</p>

      <p>Different insurers package these differently. Some include rent default by default, others as an add-on. Some have specific exclusions for vacant periods, mould, or pre-existing wear. The detail matters when the property is being sold, because the seller needs to know what is and is not covered through the campaign and the period leading up to settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why sellers must maintain cover through to settlement</h2>
      <p>Three risks make continuing landlord cover through to settlement non-negotiable. First, in Queensland the risk of loss remains with the seller until settlement. If the property burns down between contract date and settlement, the seller is responsible for putting it right or compensating the buyer. Second, even with the contract signed, the property is still the seller's asset. Until the title transfers, the seller bears the public liability risk of someone being injured on the property. Third, if the property is being sold tenanted, the tenancy continues under the existing landlord (the seller) until settlement, and rent default risk remains the seller's problem until handover.</p>

      <p>The math on cancelling cover early to save premium does not work. Saving $200 to $500 on a few weeks of premium against a potential $50,000 to $500,000 uninsured loss is not a calculation any sensible owner makes when it is laid out plainly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The interaction with the tenancy</h2>
      <p>Selling does not automatically end a tenancy. Whether the tenant remains in place during the sale, vacates partway through the campaign, or vacates close to settlement depends on the lease term, any notice given, and what the seller has agreed with the buyer.</p>

      <p>If the tenant remains in place through to settlement (a tenanted sale), the landlord-tenant relationship continues and the seller's landlord insurance remains directly relevant. Rent default protection, malicious damage cover, and the seller's public liability all stay applicable until settlement, after which the buyer assumes those obligations.</p>

      <p>If the tenant has been given notice to leave, there is often a gap between when the tenant vacates and when settlement occurs. That gap carries specific insurance implications, which most sellers overlook.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The vacant period: where most claims fail</h2>
      <p>Most landlord insurance policies have specific provisions about vacant properties. A property is typically considered "vacant" if it is unoccupied for more than a defined number of consecutive days, commonly 30 to 60. After that threshold, cover for theft, malicious damage, and water damage from internal leaks is often restricted or excluded. Some policies require notification of vacancy. Some require an additional premium for vacant property cover. Some simply void claims that occur during an unnotified vacancy.</p>

      <p>If the seller is selling with vacant possession (the buyer wants the property empty at settlement), it is common for the tenant to vacate two to four weeks before settlement to allow time for cleaning, final inspections, and any maintenance. That two to four week vacant period is exactly when fire, storm, water leak, or break-in risk is highest, because no one is living in the property to notice or report problems.</p>

      <p>The practical step is straightforward: the day the seller knows the property will be vacant for any meaningful period, notify the insurer in writing. Many insurers will adjust the policy at no cost or for a small premium loading. The risk of skipping this step is that a claim during the vacant period is denied for non-disclosure, leaving the seller carrying the full loss.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The contract disclosure point</h2>
      <p>The contract specifies whether the property is being sold with vacant possession or tenanted. That single decision drives a lot of the insurance considerations.</p>

      <p>If the property is being sold tenanted, insurance arrangements after settlement are the buyer's responsibility. The seller's landlord cover ends at settlement, the buyer arranges their own from settlement day forward, and the tenant continues uninterrupted under the new landlord. The handover of the bond, the lease, and any active maintenance issues happens at settlement.</p>

      <p>If the property is being sold with vacant possession, the seller arranges for the tenant to vacate before settlement (with proper notice and within the lease's terms). The seller maintains landlord cover through to settlement, ensures the policy contemplates the vacant period, and the buyer then arranges their own cover from settlement day. There should be no gap.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What insurers want to know at sale time</h2>
      <p>When a property is being sold, insurers want to be told. Most policies include a duty of disclosure that requires the policyholder to inform the insurer of changes that affect the risk. A pending sale, a tenant vacating, and an extended vacant period all qualify. Insurers typically want to know: that the property is being sold, the expected settlement date, when the tenant will vacate (if applicable), the property's condition and any recent claims history, and any active or unresolved claims at the time of sale.</p>

      <p>This is not a legal trap waiting to deny claims. Most insurers handle these notifications routinely and adjust the policy without difficulty. Failing to notify, however, gives the insurer grounds to dispute or deny a future claim. The simple discipline of telling the insurer when the contract is signed and again when the tenant vacates protects the policy.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Insurance and the pre-settlement inspection</h2>
      <p>If damage occurs between contract and pre-settlement inspection, the seller has obligations to both the insurer and the buyer. Notify the insurer immediately, photograph everything, get quotes for repair, and tell the buyer's solicitor through your own solicitor. Most contracts require the seller to repair insured damage before settlement, or to compensate the buyer if repair cannot be completed in time.</p>

      <p>Hiding damage and hoping the buyer does not notice at the pre-settlement inspection is a worse outcome than disclosing and resolving it. The pre-settlement inspection is specifically designed to surface this type of issue, and the buyer's solicitor will raise it formally if it appears. By that point the seller has limited time to respond, less negotiating room, and a buyer who feels misled.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Active claims during the sale</h2>
      <p>If a claim is in progress when the property goes on the market or under contract, it adds complexity to the sale but does not have to derail it. The buyer will want assurance that the repair work will be completed to acceptable standard before settlement, or in some cases will negotiate a price adjustment to take over the claim and complete the work themselves after settlement.</p>

      <p>The seller's solicitor and the insurer should coordinate to make sure the claim outcome works for both seller and buyer. Where the work cannot be completed before settlement, a negotiated holdback of funds at settlement (held by one of the solicitors) until the work is finished is a common solution. This needs to be documented properly in the contract or by separate agreement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens at settlement</h2>
      <p>At settlement the seller's landlord policy typically ends, either by the seller cancelling it from settlement date or by it lapsing as the property changes hands. The buyer arranges their own cover from settlement day onwards. Most buyers have their cover in place a day or two before settlement so there is no risk of an uninsured handover.</p>

      <p>There should be no gap in cover. Coordinate with the buyer's solicitor to confirm the buyer will have insurance in place from settlement, and only cancel the seller's cover after settlement is confirmed (most insurers will refund the unused portion of premium). If the buyer is taking over a tenanted property, transfer the bond, lease, and any active maintenance issues at settlement, and provide the buyer with the tenant's contact details and the rental ledger.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common mistakes</h2>
      <p>Three patterns show up repeatedly in disputed claims and post-sale problems. First, sellers cancelling the landlord policy at contract signing or shortly after, on the assumption that the property is "as good as sold." It is not. Until settlement, the risk is the seller's, and an uninsured event during the campaign or the pre-settlement period can be financially devastating.</p>

      <p>Second, sellers failing to notify the insurer when the tenant vacates and the property goes vacant. The vacant period is often the highest-risk period of the entire ownership, and an unnotified vacancy can void claims even where the loss has nothing to do with occupancy.</p>

      <p>Third, sellers not keeping documentary records of the tenancy, the bond, the maintenance history, and the insurance history. These records are useful for the buyer's due diligence (and may be requested in disclosure) and they are essential for any claim that needs to be substantiated. Keep them organised and hand them over at settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Treat landlord insurance as a continuous obligation that runs from the day you take ownership until the day you settle the sale. Through the sale specifically: notify the insurer when the contract is signed, notify the insurer again the day the tenant vacates (if there will be a vacant period), confirm the policy covers the vacant period or arrange specific vacant cover, maintain cover all the way through to settlement, coordinate the cover transition with the buyer so there is no gap, and keep documentation of the tenancy, the bond, and the insurance history for handover to the buyer.</p>

      <p>This is unsexy detail. It is also the difference between a smooth sale and a financially painful one in the rare case something does go wrong. The premium for a few extra weeks of cover is the cheapest insurance policy a seller will ever take out.</p>

